Task 6 - R Functions

1. Write a function that calculates the ratio of the mean and the median of a given vector. This is a helpful measure to detect data with outlying values. Note: See Reference for R language

answer: mean(x)/median(x)

2. Write a function that ignores the lowest and the highest value from a given vector and calculate the mean. answer: mean(x[-c(min(x), max(x))])

3. Read about piping from here:https://r4ds.had.co.nz/pipes.html#pipes (you don’t have to learn everything, a basic understanding of the usage is enough). Write a short (max. 300 characters, no spaces) explanation of why, how, and when not to use pipes.

Answer: For example if I were to create a plot using ggplot. Creating one long pipe could make debugging the code a challenge. Therefore it would be better to subdivide the ggplot into functioning parts and applying layers to add more features. So in essence, if you will have a long pipe, it is better to choose an alterantive.

4. Familiarize yourself with the apply-family of functions (apply, lapply, sapply etc.) http://uc-r.github.io/apply_family Write a short explanation (max. 300 characters, no spaces) of why they could be useful in your work.

Answer: Apply can be used as a fast means to understand the data, such as quickly examining means or medians. And as I used lapply later in this assigment, it is good for repetetive tasks such as transforming data or applying models. In summary, apply is suitable for fast actions and also for actions that are repetetive.

1. Compare the distributions of the body heights of the two species from the ‘magic_guys.csv’ dataset graphically

## Histograms are primarily used for distribution, this command lets you choose to see the distribution of heights and also specifically the two separate [magic_guys$species == "sith"] species. ##

a. using the basic ‘hist’ function as well as ‘ggplot’ and ‘geom_histogram’ functions from the ggplot2 package. Optimize the plots for example by trying several different ‘breaks’. Note that ggplot2-based functions give you many more options for changing the visualization parameters, try some of them.

hist(magic_guys$length)

hist(magic_guys$length, breaks = 1) ## only specifies approximately how many bins I want

hist(magic_guys$length, breaks = 50)## only specifies approximately how many bins I want

hist(magic_guys$length, breaks = 10)## only specifies approximately how many bins I want

#I deem 10 breaks to be the most optimal to correctly visualize the distribution of lengths

library(ggplot2)
library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)
##

magic_guys %>%

## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

magic_guys %>%
ggplot(aes(x=length)) +
geom_histogram(binwidth=1) #Tells the width of each bin, so reverse to the hist(x, breaks = y) function

magic_guys %>%
ggplot(aes(x=length)) +
geom_histogram(binwidth=50) #Tells the width of each bin, so reverse to the hist(x, breaks = y) function

magic_guys %>%
ggplot(aes(x=length)) +
geom_histogram(binwidth=20)

#I deem a binwidth of 20 is best for vizualizing the distribution of the data with ggplot

b. Do the same comparison as in a. but with boxplots. If you want to use the ggplot2-package, use the functions ‘ggplot’ and ‘geom_boxplot’.

boxplot(magic_guys$length ~ magic_guys$species)

magic_guys %>%
ggplot(aes(x=species, y=length)) +
geom_boxplot()

magic_guys %>%
ggplot(aes(x=species, y=length)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(shape=16, position=position_jitter(0.2))

#This gives the boxplot a good visual overview, both showing the median, IQR and extremes and also the various data points to see how the data is distributed, although the aestethics could be improved.

c. Does the number of protein coding genes or miRNAs correlate with the length of the chromosome? Make two separate plots to visualize these relationships.

chromosome %>%
  ggscatter(x = "length_mm", y = "protein_codinggenes",  
          add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, color = "red",
          cor.coef = TRUE, cor.method = "spearman")

chromosome %>%
  ggscatter(x = "length_mm", y = "mi_rna",  
          add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, color = "red",
          cor.coef = TRUE, cor.method = "spearman")

## Both protein coding genes and miRNAs correlate with the length of the chromosome, which would be expected. However miRNAs corrates stronger than protein coding genes ##
